                <div class="text">
                    <h3>Lala Mustafa Pasha Mosque - Saint Nicholas Cathedral</h3>
                    <p>Constructed during the Lusignan period between 1298 – 1312, this building is one of the most beautiful Gothic structures of the entire Mediterranean world. The Lusignans first crowned the King of Cyprus at the St. Sophia Cathedral in Nicosia, and later also the King of Jerusalem at the St. Nicholas Cathedral in Famagusta. In 1571, although it was converted into a mosque by the Ottomans, no major changes were made. The cathedral's most beautiful and well-preserved western facade was inspired by the Reims Cathedral in France.

                        The cathedral, with a unique Gothic-style window, has a 16th-century Venetian gallery in the courtyard that is still in use today as a madrasa. There is a Venetian coat of arms above the rounded entrance windows. Some animal figures are believed to have originated from a monument in Salamis. Like most Cypriot churches, the cathedral's apse is oriented eastward and is triple-bayed. The building is among the touristic attractions in the city of Famagusta.
                        
                        The windows above have been well preserved, and in front of the western facade, there are two chapels. There is a historic sycamore fig in front of the building, known locally as the "executioner’s tree" (Ficus Sycomorus). It is said that this tree was planted when construction began. A particular feature of the tree is said to bear fruit seven times a year.</p>
                    <p><a href="https://www.google.com/maps/place/Lala+Mustafa+Pa%C5%9Fa+Camii/@35.1248741,33.942514,17z/data=!3m1!4b1!4m6!3m5!1s0x14dfc83a8c129ab5:0xf11c526dd1c98205!8m2!3d35.1248741!4d33.942514!16s%2Fg%2F11k1lwks8h?entry=ttu" target="_blank" class="location">Location </a></p>
