                    <h3>Salamis Ancient City</h3>
                    <p>The history of Salamis dates back to the 11th century BC and was founded after the local people of Enkomi migrated following an earthquake. It’s particularly advisable to visit Salamis before noon as there is hardly any shade available.

                        The ancient Salamis city, about 11 km from the city of Famagusta, began to rise during the Bronze Age with influences from tribes coming from Anatolia, and these were joined by the Achaeans from Greece in Cilicia. It is believed that the city was founded by Teucer, son of Telamon, the king of Salamis Island and hero of Troy. After the Assyrian dominance in 707 BC, it is understood that Salamis King Evelthon gained control of the region around 560 BC, as inferred from the coins minted. In 499 BC, Athenian general Kimon ended the Persian rule in Cyprus with a successful military expedition but passed away, and the Athenians subsequently abandoned their intentions of controlling Cyprus. Later, Phoenician traders took over, but trade and other areas began to decline. In 411 BC, members of the Teucrid family, especially Evagoras, managed to take over the rule of Salamis.
                        
                        To maintain control over the entire island, Salamis was frequently besieged by the Persians and had to pay tribute to the Persian King. This situation continued until the time of Alexander the Great. The Salamis King Pythagoras, because he provided military assistance to Alexander, was rewarded with the city of Tamassus after Alexander's death. Alexander's successors changed hands continuously in Salamis. Under the administration of Ptolemaic Egypt beginning in 294 BC, Cyprus found peace, and Salamis continued as the island's capital city throughout the Roman domination.
                        
                        Most of today's ruins date back to the Roman period. Under Roman rule, the city had its own senate and council of elders. The city was heavily damaged by the Jewish revolts in 76 and 77 AD and by earthquakes in 116 AD. Later, the island was attached to the province of Antioch, and because Salamis port was the first stop for ships coming from Syria, the city achieved a significant prominence. Large earthquakes in 232 and 342 AD caused great damage to the city. Following this, Byzantine Emperor Constantine had the city rebuilt on a smaller scale and named it Constantia. The city of Baf, now known as Paphos, became the capital of Cyprus. Later, due to the Arab invasions and earthquakes around 647 AD, the city was abandoned, and the population migrated to the region which now forms the modern city of Famagusta.</p>
                    <p><a href="https://www.google.com/maps/place/Salamis+Harabeleri/@35.1870645,33.903535,17z/data=!3m1!4b1!4m6!3m5!1s0x14dfb7d18cb30f81:0xc4730b27ee43c6e0!8m2!3d35.1870645!4d33.903535!16s%2Fg%2F11v63w83qx?hl=tr&entry=ttu" target="_blank" class="location">Location</a></p>
                </div>
